  "prompt": "Why can't the government of India resolve water crisis all over India by using the river water that flows into the ocean?",
  "response": "There are several complex reasons why the Indian government cannot simply use all river water that flows into the ocean to resolve water crisis:\n\n1. Technical Challenges:\n- Massive infrastructure requirements\n- High cost of water transportation\n- Engineering complexities\n- Terrain and geographical barriers\n\n2. Water Distribution Issues:\n- Uneven rainfall distribution across regions\n- Seasonal variations in river water flow\n- Different river basin characteristics\n- Variability in water quality\n\n3. Ecological Considerations:\n- Maintaining ecological balance\n- Preserving river ecosystem\n- Preventing saltwater intrusion\n- Protecting marine life\n\n4. Interstate Water Disputes:\n- Conflicting water sharing agreements\n- Political tensions between states\n- Legal complications\n- Lack of consensus on water distribution\n\n5. Financial Constraints:\n- Enormous investment required\n- Limited government budget\n- High implementation costs\n- Technological challenges\n\n6. Geographical Limitations:\n- Long distances between water sources\n- Difficult topographical conditions\n- Energy requirements for water transportation\n\n7. Legal and Policy Challenges:\n- Complex water rights\n- Regulatory framework limitations\n- Inter-state water sharing agreements\n\n8. Environmental Impact:\n- Potential disruption of natural water cycles\n- Risk of environmental degradation\n\nThese multifaceted challenges make comprehensive water crisis resolution complex and challenging.",
